B.Lr=new A.f_(1,"Basic Anatomy","Unit 1: The pancreas and body systems","NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd pancreas\nMedlinePlus \ufffd Digestive System","https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/pancreas\nhttps://medlineplus.gov/digestivesystem.html",u.u,"The pancreas is an organ. An organ is a body part made of tissues, and a tissue is made of many cells. The pancreas is a gland because it makes useful substances for the body. It helps the digestive system by sending enzymes through a duct to help break down food. It also helps the endocrine system by making hormones, which are chemical messages that travel in the blood. So the pancreas has two big jobs: helping digest food and helping control blood sugar.","This course now starts with very basic body words. Read the passage, then answer three questions.",B.NA,B.OF)
B.Pd=s(["Cell membrane","Cytoplasm","Nucleus","DNA","Gene","Chromosome","Protein","Receptor","Signal","Cell division","Mitosis"],t.s)
B.N4=s(["In the nucleus","Only outside the body","In the duct","In food only"],t.s)
B.LF=new A.cI("Where is DNA found in this lesson?",B.N4,0)
B.MQ=s(["It receives a signal","It becomes a whole organ","It turns into bone","It stores bile"],t.s)
B.Ly=new A.cI("What does a receptor do?",B.MQ,0)
B.OI=s(["A type of cell division","A kind of infection","A surgery","A hormone"],t.s)
B.Lz=new A.cI("What is mitosis?",B.OI,0)
B.OR=s([B.LF,B.Ly,B.Lz],t.EF)
B.Lm=new A.f_(2,"Basic Cell Biology","Unit 2: Inside a cell","MedlinePlus Genetics \ufffd What is a cell?\nMedlinePlus Genetics \ufffd What is DNA?\nMedlinePlus Genetics \ufffd What is a chromosome?","https://medlineplus.gov/genetics/understanding/basics/cell/\nhttps://medlineplus.gov/genetics/understanding/basics/dna/\nhttps://medlineplus.gov/genetics/understanding/basics/chromosome/","Adapted from MedlinePlus Genetics in simpler language.","A cell has parts with different jobs. The cell membrane is the outside layer that helps protect the cell. Inside is the cytoplasm, a jelly-like material where many cell jobs happen. The nucleus is the part that holds DNA. DNA contains genes, and genes are instructions for making proteins. Proteins help cells work. Cells also use receptors to receive a signal from outside the cell. When a cell gets the right signal, it may grow or divide. Cell division is how one cell becomes two cells, and mitosis is one common kind of cell division.","Now move inside the cell and learn the words that appear in basic biology.",B.Pd,B.OR)
B.O_=s(["Cancer","Tumor","Benign","Malignant","Growth","Spread","Metastasis","Invasion","Mass","Lesion"],t.s)
B.Nz=s(["An abnormal mass of cells","A healthy hormone","A type of white blood cell","A duct full of enzymes"],t.s)
B.LE=new A.cI("What is a tumor?",B.Nz,0)
B.LY=s(["Cancerous and able to invade or spread","Always harmless","Part of normal digestion","A kind of imaging test"],t.s)
B.Lt=new A.cI("What does malignant mean?",B.LY,0)
B.Oc=s(["Cancer spreading to another part of the body","A cell fixing DNA","The body making insulin","A type of exercise"],t.s)
B.LC=new A.cI("What is metastasis?",B.Oc,0)
B.NZ=s([B.LE,B.Lt,B.LC],t.EF)
B.Ln=new A.f_(3,"Basic Cancer Terms","Unit 3: Cancer, tumors, and spread","NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd cancer\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd tumor\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd metastasis","https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/cancer\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/tumor\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/metastasis","Adapted from NCI in simpler language.","Cancer is a disease in which cells grow too much and do not follow normal rules. A tumor is a mass, or lump, made of abnormal cells. Some tumors are benign, which means they are not cancer and are not expected to spread. Other tumors are malignant, which means they are cancer and can invade nearby tissue. If cancer cells spread far away and grow in a new place, that is called metastasis. Doctors may also use the word lesion for an area of abnormal tissue seen on a scan or in the body.","These are the first cancer words a beginner should know.",B.O_,B.NZ)
B.Pi=s(["Mutation","Inheritance","Genetic change","DNA damage","Repair"],t.s)
B.Pe=s(["A change in DNA","A type of scan","A body system","A kind of swelling"],t.s)
B.LD=new A.cI("What is a mutation?",B.Pe,0)
B.NR=s(["Receiving genes or traits from parents","Getting medicine from a store","Breaking down food","Losing weight quickly"],t.s)
B.LH=new A.cI("What does inheritance mean here?",B.NR,0)
B.OS=s(["Because cells try to fix DNA damage","Because it changes bones into muscles","Because it stops all disease forever","Because it is the same as metastasis"],t.s)
B.LK=new A.cI("Why is repair important?",B.OS,0)
B.Nd=s([B.LD,B.LH,B.LK],t.EF)
B.Lq=new A.f_(4,"Basic Genetics","Unit 4: DNA changes and inheritance","MedlinePlus Genetics \ufffd What is DNA?\nMedlinePlus Genetics \ufffd What is a gene?\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd mutation","https://medlineplus.gov/genetics/understanding/basics/dna/\nhttps://medlineplus.gov/genetics/understanding/basics/gene/\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/46063","Adapted from MedlinePlus Genetics and NCI in simpler language.","Genes are written in DNA, and DNA can change. A mutation is a change in DNA. Some genetic changes are inherited, which means they are passed from parent to child. Other changes happen later during life. DNA can also be damaged by mistakes or by harmful exposures. Cells have repair systems that try to fix DNA damage. When repair does not work well, more genetic changes can build up over time.","This unit keeps genetics simple and focuses on the words beginners see first.",B.Pi,B.Nd)
B.NC=s(["Disease","Disorder","Infection","Inflammation","Pain","Swelling","Jaundice","Weight loss"],t.s)
B.N8=s(["A body response to injury or infection","A kind of surgery","A normal chromosome","A digestive enzyme"],t.s)
B.LJ=new A.cI("What is inflammation?",B.N8,0)
B.MT=s(["Yellowing of the skin or eyes","A broken bone","A type of blood test","A healthy cell membrane"],t.s)
B.Lv=new A.cI("What does jaundice describe?",B.MT,0)
B.M1=s(["A disease caused by germs","Any operation done by a doctor","A family history","A way cells divide"],t.s)
B.Lx=new A.cI("What is an infection?",B.M1,0)
B.MV=s([B.LJ,B.Lv,B.Lx],t.EF)
B.Lj=new A.f_(5,"Basic Disease Terms","Unit 5: Symptoms and body changes","MedlinePlus \ufffd Inflammation\nMedlinePlus \ufffd Jaundice","https://medlineplus.gov/inflammation.html\nhttps://medlineplus.gov/jaundice.html","Adapted from MedlinePlus in simpler language.","A disease or disorder is a health problem that changes how the body works. Some diseases are caused by infection, while others are not. Inflammation is a body response to injury or infection and can lead to pain and swelling. Jaundice means yellowing of the skin or eyes. Weight loss can also be a sign that the body is under stress or not getting enough nutrition. These words do not name one single disease, but they help people describe what is happening in the body.","A new learner also needs common disease words and symptom words.",B.NC,B.MV)
B.Ng=s(["Test","Scan","Imaging","Blood test","Biopsy","Sample","Salivary testing","Diagnosis"],t.s)
B.Nf=s(["A small tissue or cell sample taken for testing","A kind of hormone","A way to stop all pain right away","A type of family history"],t.s)
B.LA=new A.cI("What is a biopsy?",B.Nf,0)
B.Np=s(["Finding out what disease or condition a person has","Making food easier to digest","Turning a benign tumor into a malignant one","Teaching a cell to divide"],t.s)
B.LG=new A.cI("What does diagnosis mean?",B.Np,0)
B.P3=s(["Making pictures of the inside of the body","Writing down genes with a pencil","A type of infection","A hormone made by the pancreas"],t.s)
B.Ls=new A.cI("What is imaging?",B.P3,0)
