B.Ll=new A.f_(6,"Basic Diagnosis","Unit 6: Tests and finding a diagnosis","NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd biopsy\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd CT scan\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd MRI","https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/biopsy\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/ct-scan\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/mri","Adapted from NCI in simpler language.","Doctors use tests to learn what is happening in the body. A scan is a picture made with a machine, and imaging is the general word for making those pictures. A blood test uses a blood sample. A biopsy uses a small tissue or cell sample. Salivary testing means testing saliva, or spit, for useful information. All of these tools can help with diagnosis, which means finding out what disease or condition a person has.","This unit explains the very basic words used when doctors look for answers.",B.Ng,B.Nh)
B.N5=s(["Treatment","Surgery","Medicine","Chemotherapy","Radiation","Therapy","Recovery"],t.s)
B.Nl=s(["Drug treatment used to kill cancer cells or slow their growth","A kind of digestive enzyme","A way to measure age","A type of family history"],t.s)
B.LL=new A.cI("What is chemotherapy?",B.Nl,0)
B.P5=s(["Getting better after illness or treatment","A new kind of tumor","A receptor on the cell membrane","A scan of the pancreas only"],t.s)
B.LI=new A.cI("What does recovery mean?",B.P5,0)
B.OQ=s(["Treatment done with an operation","A signal inside a cell","A type of swelling","A damaged gene"],t.s)
B.LO=new A.cI("What is surgery?",B.OQ,0)
B.N9=s([B.LL,B.LI,B.LO],t.EF)
B.Lp=new A.f_(7,"Basic Treatment","Unit 7: Ways doctors treat disease","NCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd treatment\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd chemotherapy\nNCI Dictionary of Cancer Terms \ufffd radiation therapy","https://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/treatment\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/chemotherapy\nhttps://www.cancer.gov/publications/dictionaries/cancer-terms/def/radiation-therapy","Adapted from NCI in simpler language.","Treatment is care used to help a disease or condition. Surgery is treatment done with an operation. Medicine is a drug used to help the body. Chemotherapy is a kind of medicine used to kill cancer cells or slow their growth. Radiation is high-energy treatment used against some cancers. Therapy is a broad word for treatment, and recovery means getting better after illness or treatment. Different people may need different treatments depending on the disease and how far it has gone.","After diagnosis comes treatment. This unit keeps those treatment words simple.",B.N5,B.N9)
